<body>
  <!-- 20 · CLOSING / TAKEAWAYS -->
  <section class="slide closing">
    <div class="head">
      <h1 class="title">STP picks the rung the brand asks the buyer to <em>remember it on</em>.</h1>
      <div class="rule"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="grid">
      <div class="takeaways">
        <div class="t">
          <span class="n">01</span>
          <span class="txt"><strong>Cut on the benefit, not just the label.</strong> The benefit is the cause of the choice.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="t">
          <span class="n">02</span>
          <span class="txt"><strong>Target the segment you can win.</strong> Compatibility comes before attractiveness.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="t">
          <span class="n">03</span>
          <span class="txt"><strong>An empty quadrant is an opening only when buyers cluster in it.</strong> Otherwise it is dead air.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="t">
          <span class="n">04</span>
          <span class="txt"><strong>STP picks the category; the penetration laws govern growth.</strong> Then reach more category buyers.</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="aside">
        <div>
          <h4>Next chapter</h4>
          <p class="preview">Ch. 7 — <em>Brands and brand management</em>: building the position into memory.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="when">From choosing the position to defending the web of associations that carries it.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="source">MKTG 4333 · Chapter 6 · Segmentation, Targeting, Positioning</p>
  </section>
